:::summary
Marcus Aurelius (AD 121–180) was Roman Emperor from 161 to 180 and a devoted Stoic philosopher. His private journal, known as the *Meditations*, is one of the most celebrated works of philosophical reflection ever written — a record of a ruler's daily effort to live virtuously, govern justly, and face suffering and death with equanimity. He is often called the last of the "Five Good Emperors" and the philosopher-king whom Plato envisioned.
:::

